@davidhilton7780Thank you! Not an original idea by any means. In fact you can see evidence of this kind of dielectric barrier charge pump in Nikola Tesla's original patent "Apparatus for the utilization of radiant energy." US685957A.

Tesla was among the first to suspect that the ionic content of the air is sustained by a combination of heat from the Sun, lightning, and ultraviolet and high energy cosmic radiation. The problem was always how to use that energy since ion density is usually so low. The solution, according to Tesla and some modern experimenters, is using exceptionally thin but high-K dielectrics. Tesla was limited to Mica and other relatively weak dielectrics, but once the critical breakdown of air is  overcome, the plasma has highly non-linear electrical properties that make it ideal for converting different kinds of random environmental energies into useful work in the ground circuit. 

In fact the design should act very similarly to a recent invention that the famous Richard Feynman predicted was impossible. A class of Maxwell's Demon known as Brownian Ratchets was recently experimentally confirmed by using the Brownian motion of Graphene to extract energy from random thermal fluctuations in a single equilibrium thermal bath rather than from two thermal baths not in equilibrium. By suppressing the temperature fluctuations in the room the Laws of Thermodynamics are not violated, even though power is flowing in a system that is in thermodynamic equilibrium ie. the room and the graphene and the circuit is all the same temperature. It turns out that classical thermodynamics just won't do. The correct model must include the statistical thermodynamics of all the microstates of the quantized particles in the system to describe the uncertainty or distribution of fluctuation in the temperature flowing around in a classically equilibrium system. By reducing the fluctuations in temperature, the average temperature doesn't shift much, but the uncertainty or fluctuations do go away, leaving an even more uniform temperature that never left equilibrium. Like noise cancellation. The reduced uncertainty is the source of increasing entropy to perform work on the circuit. A dielectric barrier discharge that forms a plasma double layer can perform a similar role as a "Brownian Ratchet" by being a highly non-linear medium that can amplify fluctuations coupled to the circuit. A plasma panel would act as an anechoic panel that could absorb sound waves and random temperature fluctuations in a room until the temperature was uniform everywhere (in a perfectly sealed room). Put it outside and you have many sources of fluctuations that can be harvested.
